AMLA	date_of_periodic_review	The date of periodic review is the point in time when the financial institution regularly checks the customer's data and risk profile to ensure they are up-to-date and comply with regulatory requirements. The purpose of periodic reviews is to keep the customer's data accurate and current, and to enable the institution to timely identify and manage potential risks.
AMLA	due_date_of periodic_review	"The due date of periodic review is the point in time when the financial institution must regularly check the customer's data and risk profile to ensure they are up-to-date and comply with regulatory requirements. This date indicates when the next review should be conducted and helps the institution timely identify and manage potential risks.
The frequency of periodic reviews can vary depending on the customer's risk classification. For example, high-risk customers may be reviewed annually, medium-risk customers every two years, and low-risk customers every three years. The institution's policies and procedures determine the frequency of periodic reviews for different customers."
