AMLA	offboarding_date	From a compliance perspective, the termination of the business relationship refers to the specific point in time when the financial institution, in accordance with applicable laws and internal regulations, actually closes the client’s account and thereby ends the business relationship.
AMLA	offboarding_initiator	The department who initiated the customer's offboarding. E.g.: KYC, AML
AMLA	offboarding_type	"Types of business relationship termination include immediate offboarding and offboarding with prior notice.
Immediate offboarding occurs when the business relationship ends without delay, and the account is closed promptly. The customer is informed as soon as possible. This approach is typically applied in cases of serious compliance or legal concerns, such as suspected money laundering or fraud.
Offboarding with prior notice means the business relationship ends after a defined notice period. During this time, the customer is informed of the upcoming termination and given the opportunity to resolve any outstanding obligations. This method is generally used in less severe situations, such as failure to meet account maintenance requirements.
In both cases, accurate documentation and strict adherence to compliance regulations are essential to ensure the financial institution’s legal and regulatory compliance and to safeguard the customer’s rights."
AMLA	PEP	"Politically exposed person: a natural person who is entrusted with prominent public functions, or who has been entrusted with such functions within the period preceding the implementation of customer due diligence measures, as specified in local legislation;
Family member of a politically exposed person:
a) the spouse, or a person considered to be equivalent to a spouse, of a politically exposed person;
b) the children and their spouses, or persons considered to be equivalent to a spouse, of a politically exposed person;
c) the parents of a politically exposed person;
Person known to be a close associate to a politically exposed person:
a) natural persons who are known to have joint beneficial ownership of legal entities or legal arrangements, or any other close business relations, with a politically exposed person;
b) natural persons who have sole beneficial ownership of a legal entity or legal arrangement which is known to have been set up for the de facto benefit of a politically exposed person"
AMLA	reason _for_offboarding	If the business relationship is terminated, the reason for termination must be thoroughly documented (e.g., terminated by CMP). Accurately recording the reason for termination is essential for compliance processes, as it helps identify the factors that led to the end of the relationship. This information plays a crucial role in the internal control and auditing processes of financial institutions, as well as in maintaining legal and financial compliance. The termination of the business relationship is executed through the offboarding process, which includes closing the account and completing all necessary compliance and operational steps.
AMLA	relevant_customer	"Compliance customer
any natural or legal person who, in a contract concluded with the OTP Group, appears as a debtor, co-debtor, collateral debtor, account holder, co-owner, or in any other role that is significant from the perspective of AML or other compliance risks. This includes, for example, participants in current accounts, deposit accounts, credit accounts, securities accounts, but also unidentified cash depositors.

The following, for example, are not considered compliance customers:
•    Participants who are included in the system solely for technical or administrative purposes (e.g., test customers).
•    A participant associated with a transaction or contract type that does not pose a risk from a compliance perspective and is not relevant from an AML perspective (e.g., subsidies)."
